I frequently see people calling the 68000 a 16-bit processor, which irritates me to no end. It may have a 16-bit data bus, but it has 32-bit registers and 32-bit addressing (though truncated to 24 bits externally). It's a 32-bit processor, just a partially crippled one. By the 68020, they were fully 32-bit, and guess what? No backwards-incompatible 32-bit mode (though a lot of software wouldn't work with full 32-bit addressing for various reasons). It...Read moreI frequently see people calling the 68000 a 16-bit processor, which irritates me to no end. It may have a 16-bit data bus, but it has 32-bit registers and 32-bit addressing (though truncated to 24 bits externally). Itâ€™s a 32-bit processor, just a partially crippled one. By the 68020, they were fully 32-bit, and guess what? No backwards-incompatible 32-bit mode (though a lot of software wouldnâ€™t work with full 32-bit addressing for various reasons). It really was a superior chip to the 8086 by a long way, but of course IBM had to get the PC out as fast as possible and couldnâ€™t wait for Motorola to fix their issuesâ€¦
